Roman ruins in the heart of Paris!  The Cluny museum has incorporated the Roman baths as part of their exhibition space.  The only way to go inside is to pay for the Cluny Medieval Art Museum tour.  Well worth it though!

As a Roman history buff and someone who studied them in UG I was a bit ashamed to be caught unawares of this gem in the middle of Paris. Head to the Musee de Cluny and pay the 5 Euro entrance fee. Then go downstairs into this incredibly well preserved Frigidarium. What a treat! I took out my phone and called my friends back stateside and talked for an hour, just taking it all in subconsciously while down there, surrounded by Roman ingenuity. Thanks Paris (Lutetia)!

From the 3rd century thermal baths were built in Lut√©ce. The thermal baths of Cluny were undoubtedly built by the powerful corporation of Nautes Parisiens. In fact, the vault room has a structure in the shape of a ship and the decorations with fish motifs confirm this hypothesis. Gallo-Roman cohabitation was to allow members of the Brotherhood of Nautes free access to the thermal baths. All that remains is the coldest room of the thermal baths (the frigidarium) where you can notice the lines of red bricks which are a Roman architectural mark found throughout the Mediterranean basin. This structure, strong enough to have survived to this day, once supported a hanging garden with trees. The thermal baths were cleared and restored under the order of Louis 18.
